===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|tool|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|tol|tōl|tool, implement, instrument|lit=that with which one prepares something|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|tōlą||tool|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|dewǝ-||to tie to, secure|lang=ine-pro}}, equivalent to {{suffix|taw|t1=to prepare|le}} {{gloss|agent suffix}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|tuil||tool, implement, instrument, device|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|is|
-}} {{term|tól||tool|lang=is}}, {{etyl|fo|-}} {{term|tól||tool, instrument|lang=fo}}. Related to {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|tawian|tāwian|to make, prepare, or cultivate|lang=ang}}; see {{l|en|taw}}, and {{l|en|tow}} ("fibres used for spinning").<ref>{{reference-book|last=Carus|first=Paul|title=The philosophy of the tool|publisher=The Open Court Publishing Company|pages=3-4|location=Chicago|date=1893|ref=refCarus1893}}</ref><ref>{{reference-book|last=Hall|first=John Richard Clark|others=Supplement by Herbert D. Merritt|title=A Concise Anglo-Saxon Dictionary|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=338 & 345|origyear=1960|year=1984|edition=4|isbn=9780802065483|ref=refHall1984}}</ref>

